<section id="section-6">
<title>Exercises</title>
<para id="element-95a">
<exercise id="exercise-95a">
<problem id="idp9142720">
<para id="element-95">
Which of the following is/ are independent of the angle of projection of a projectile :


</para>
<para id="element-96">
      (a)  time of flight
</para>
<para id="element-97">
      (b) maximum height reached
</para>
<para id="element-98">
      (c) acceleration of projectile
</para>
<para id="element-99">
      (d) horizontal component of velocity


</para>
</problem>

<solution id="idm2158816">
<para id="element-100">
The time of flight is determined by considering vertical motion.  It means that time of flight is dependent on speed and the angle of projection.

</para>

<para id="element-101">
<m:math display="block">
  <m:mrow>
    <m:mi>T</m:mi>
    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    <m:mfrac>
      <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        <m:msub>
          <m:mi>u</m:mi>
          <m:mi>y</m:mi>
        </m:msub>
      </m:mrow>
      <m:mi>g</m:mi>
    </m:mfrac>
    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    <m:mfrac>
      <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        <m:mi>u</m:mi>
        <m:mi>sin</m:mi>
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:mrow>
      <m:mi>g</m:mi>
    </m:mfrac>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>

</para>
<para id="element-102">
Maximum height is also determined, considering vertical motion. As such, maximum height also depends on the angle of projection.

</para>
<para id="element-103">
<m:math display="block">
  <m:mrow>
    <m:mi>H</m:mi>
    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    <m:mfrac>
      <m:mrow>
        <m:msubsup>
          <m:mi>u</m:mi>
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mi>y</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        </m:msubsup>
      </m:mrow>
      <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        <m:mi>g</m:mi>
      </m:mrow>
    </m:mfrac>
    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    <m:mfrac>
      <m:mrow>
        <m:msup>
          <m:mi>u</m:mi>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        </m:msup>
        <m:msup>
          <m:mi>sin</m:mi>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        </m:msup>
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:mrow>
      <m:mrow>
        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        <m:mi>g</m:mi>
      </m:mrow>
    </m:mfrac>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>

</para>
<para id="element-104">
Horizontal component, being component of velocity, depends on the angle of projection.

</para>
<para id="element-105">
<m:math display="block">
  <m:mrow>
    <m:msub>
      <m:mi>u</m:mi>
      <m:mi>y</m:mi>
    </m:msub>
    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
    <m:mi>u</m:mi>
    <m:mi>cos</m:mi>
    <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>

</para>
<para id="element-106">
It is only the acceleration of projectile, which is equal to acceleration due to gravity and is, therefore, independent of the angle of projection. Hence, option (c) is correct.   
</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</para>




<para id="element-107a">
<exercise id="exercise-107a">
<problem id="idp9616800">
<para id="element-107">
Two particles are projected with same initial speeds at 30° and 60° with the horizontal. Then 

</para>
